Imaginez une très longue page Web avec beaucoup de sections (p. ex., des spécifications sur une seule page HTML). Si l'utilisateur demande une section précise (p. ex. page.html#section7), que se passerait-il si le serveur web streamait d'abord cette section, puis les autres?
Order of the stream:
1. beginning of the HTML document up to <body>
2. HTML for section 7
3. HTML for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
The browser would then ensure to insert sections 1 to 6 *above* section 7 on the web page.
Is that clear? It could be useful?
What I want to achieve is to have the rendering of the linked section (#section7) as fast as possible without having to reimplement anything with JavaScript. I just want to have a super long HTML document, but with the rendering of linked sections as fast as possible. It should work with HTML.
The content could be streamed in this way, and then the browser would inject each <contents> into its <div>.
<div id="sec1"></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
It would be streamed in disorder, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it were streamed in order.
@user22 You can reorganize the documents like that even without JS. You cannot use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string search parameters to tell the server which section you want to see first. To reorganize the sections, you have the choice between:
1. Using cascading style sheets
2. Using a template with placeholders
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not correspond to the order of the DOM. It could be useful to have an HTML feature that allows streaming out of order, and the browser would then reorganize the DOM content in the correct order.
But the approach by positioning seems promising. I will try.
@user22 oh, you want the browser to correct the DOM order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first only to allow the user to see it as soon as possible. It would be good if it could do that without affecting the DOM order, so that the browser can ensure that the resulting DOM order corresponds to the visual order.
In other words, stream section 7 first, but make sure the final result (DOM and visual) is as if all sections had been streamed in order.
@user22 @user23 Take a look at PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
